An extreme struggle: MP3 players against mobiles.
You will be advised, how to choose
While almost all mobiles can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can telephone.
It seems to be clear that it is better to buy only one phone.
Don’t stop there are enough reasons for obtaining an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy a high-end gramophone to put the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such music products do not come out on vinyl disc, and from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to occur.
But if there are vinyl discs in your staircases, with art rock, jazz or blues, you at least probably dream of such a gramophone.
It is the same for music during the moves, namely compressed music, to say it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
There are also categories depending on price and quality.
For one, it can be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, in the same way as a fan of the Pink Floyd would have difficulty carrying earphones purchased for twenty crowns on the market.
Here are two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The battery life is also decisive
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are unknown features, of course, in most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to first functions, telephone calls and SMS sending, it is able to read music and movies, record them, it has a variable quality camera and may, for example, use to navigate.
And if you take into account smartphones and communications, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator can grind meat and no television will take photographs, we are practically watching a miracle.
But the universal character of the mobile is not without disadvantages.
The larger the number of functions you use, the lower the interval between two recharges will be seen.
And playing music is one of the most important energies.
There are rare mobiles that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this number is significantly lower.
In this regard, music players (especially the most rudimentary) are significantly more performing.
In the case of cheap mobiles, consider that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, it comes to calling you from time to time, get, to be over, a second recharge for work - this applies even to the most expensive devices.
This will not be a problem for MP3 players, who are able, after a recharge, to have a continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the less performing.
Another problem occurs when recording music on the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, so much more than everyone can be connected directly to the computer, without a special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but few card readers know to take it without reduction, given the small dimensions of memory cards used in mobiles.
With regard to readers, you do not need, except for (iPod), any software.
Just fill, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will create a media library classified by the name of the interpreter, the title of the album, the style, or then by the user's judgment.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, as Windows Explore, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to manipulate, mobiles have more knowledge
In choosing a concrete apparatus, you are especially interested in the battery life, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If music is essentially a background noise for you, and if in the day you’re going to listen to it only for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, it’s enough for you to read any mobile MP3.
Almost all mobiles are able to do so today.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to read.
Everyone can read the MP3 and the vast majority of music that will come to you until you have this format.
It is one of the most common formats, and besides it, the vast majority of devices can also read WMA format music.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods), as regards it, is less common.
High-range mobiles also allow, for example, online purchase of music.
Just visit, from the mobile phone, the corresponding web pages of the operator (or those of another provider) and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a convincing reason for purchasing a musical mobile.
The offer of operators is unfortunately miserable and it is, in most cases, limited to fast-made radio tubes.
Prices are also not the lowest.
However, it is generally considered that this way of purchasing music (whether by GSM, the internet, or even by wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their mobile on their own.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to get the mobile out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
It’s also important if you always have headphones or a handheld with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use built-in pregnancies, which have almost all mobiles, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of music mobiles is their price.
The cheapest usually costs less than 3,000.
For a price of 3,000 crowns, you can have a walkman already very convenient.
But, in most cases, you will be limited by the absence of output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best-equipped, also provided with an entry for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, however, have the advantage of having an easy order.
True, anyone who manages to ensure the order of the rudimentary readers - who do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (see our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the command with that of a cassette post, commonly used in the past, or of a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by an immense data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g., Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models support only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive can even come out with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1 100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, instead choose the specialized mobile-walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and so the control failure approaches that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman series mobiles have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that has gone farther in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a lifetime of the battery (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours) above, is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the above brands.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Or maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, our operators offer virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still miss something - a virtual operator, which would force classic operators to lower prices.
It may not be missing for a long time.
We have repeatedly mentioned on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are one of the most expensive in Europe.
The Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), which reported that the price of a SMS was higher with us than in the rest of the Union, confirmed.
This is why, following the European Commission's last steps in the area of roaming fees regulation, a paradoxal situation is likely to occur – SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper for some Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the battle.
This may seem paradoxal, since we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that largely exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators love to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who repeatedly stated that there was no room for another operator in the Czech Republic, made chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with his own network apparently has much more luck (otherwise, now it would only find frequencies hard).
But there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It was just the entry of virtual operators to the mobile market that led to a significant drop in prices, to which they subsequently also had to respond to classic operators.
Nevertheless, even before the entry of trouble feasts such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those we hear today at our home were left to be heard in the UK.
But it seemed that there was room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We are not forced to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch, in Poland, of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Adding that behind the Mobilking, there is the Penta financial group, which, among other things, owns the U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
In order for their operation to be effective, they actually need much less customers than a classic operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the cost of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network, relatively high.
This is how virtual operators in the world profile themselves as low-cost operators – they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers in the UK at least twice less expensive SMS than its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, bet on an unusual target group can also be a good hit of advertising.
In fact, this operator specifically targets men.
“Real men choose Mobilking – an operator they like and they can trust,” said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, exploiting this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would likely be able to walk at home as well.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone’s spokeswoman, doubts: “The Czech market is relatively small for a segmentary approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
As far as it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service supply."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are discussing the successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very promoting.
The launch of Mobilking will rather take place in other countries of our area,” said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, Penta Financial Group spokeswoman.
It therefore indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not favourable to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything they can so that a potential competitor can not appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of business customers, has not hidden, long enough, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We have a lot to be able to offer to our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile services.
And the sooner it will be the best.
We have already negotiated this possibility several times with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl Group spokeswoman.
Maybe the future is promising.
According to non-official information, it seems that we might be able to welcome the first virtual operator before the end of the year.
But for the moment, its creation is accompanied by a total silence.
“Now, we don’t think there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is very specific in comparison with others.
For the moment, no subject has been involved in a complex and serious project in this field has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sršeň from the Telefonika O2 press department, in its statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová said in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not registered for the moment a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a base."
"It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator appears in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate in such a limited time, we should now have a concrete agreement.”
Vodafone focuses on fulfilling requests to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický said in this respect: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the field of shared costs and infrastructure.
That’s what we think is the most input from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field is the discovery of a partner to set up a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean a rise in competition, would have led to a price drop and thus a decrease in their profits.
So what is good to facilitate the arrival of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to hear each other as larron in fairs. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to it.
The most apparent pressure on the ČTÚ, during the creation of the U:fon, was that of the company T-Mobile.
Providing information accessible to the public from the websites of the ČTÚ.
Today, U:fon is ready to use itself as an argument to not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted this: “Competition on the mobile market has been recently enlarged by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player, and especially its services, would submit it to high demands."
However, given the attitude of the mobile operators herein, the indifference of the Czech regulators appears to be disregarding.
However, it is not only the attitude of the ČTÚ, which, unlike the UK and other developed countries, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic does not have the power to intervene in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
But the latter adopted, faced with this problem, his typical position.
The entry of a virtual operator to the mobile market would be possible as a result of the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded at the moment, as the offer of potential stakeholders has a priori not presented sufficient interest for classical operators," said Kristián Chalupa in response to our question at the UOHS Department of Foreign Relations.
A statement thus made would not be surprised by the representatives of the operators.
But from one office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among others, also take care, that no one profits from his position on the market, such a statement is more than disruptive.
More than Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the foreign country, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be found that their market entry has contributed to a lower price of mobile phone services."
But pressing in the sense of fair functioning of the market and price drops is apparently not part of the interests of the UOHS.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which is derived from their reactions.
The question, if this is really an accident, is natural.
Similarly, a gasoline price is strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to random and hard fighting competition.
"The Office did not raise any signs of anti-competitive behavior in this regard, so it has no reason to interfere in one way or another.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore none has an increased accountability for their behaviour in the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably lacking even the telecommunications regulator,” Chaloupa said in a statement.
Interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ that telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some law experts offer a different vision of things: in order to make a virtual operator possible, each time we need to obtain the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has logically enough monopoly on its network.
This is how he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should at least be concerned for the UOHS that three mobile operators are visiblely proceeding in a similar way.
However, the complaints of many stakeholders (including the company GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
To regain responsibility on the ČTÚ is a fairly common turn in communications, through which the ÚOHS washs the hands of the case.
We have already met this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, we have failed to bring about the newization of the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, an extension of the powers of the ČTÚ in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised to improve the situation.
This is what the representatives of the UOHS have to know, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can walk
This says that the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, many in the Czech mobile networks, remains unrecognized.
These companies are publishing their own price list of mobile phone services, but these are only public in part.
In most cases, it is about multi-level marketing companies.
Personalized mobile phone services are offered, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
Price lists of these companies usually only arrive at elected ones.
The magic tour consists in the fact that the company is made in front of the operator is a classic business client, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special prizes (and other) offers.
What makes a problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such sales.
"If what you're talking about happened, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions we'd examine and which could lead to a cease-fire of cooperation with the company in question," Martina Kemrová replied.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such an activity has not been achieved to the managers of mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned there may be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, pronounces against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these companies provide unnecessary profits, and at the same time, in contrast to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them at all with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický indicates the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card on their phone is not recorded under their name, so they can’t have it fully, in the way of ordinary customers of mobile operators.”
But that is exactly what should look strange to the ČTÚ.
In addition, another question is raised to the UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the UOHS has relatively broad powers to disclose such an activity, and if it does not want to meet the explanations of the operators, who claim no idea that this would occur, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a significant decline in the price of services.
However, in almost all countries where virtual operators appeared, classic operators, sometimes more, sometimes less, endeavored to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
At that level, however, the regulators intervened in the developed countries, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
As well as by formal measures as by informal pressure, they eventually gained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are dealing with this issue in the way a hot potato can get rid of it by transmitting it to a nearby target.
Following the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in their skills is more than profitable in these cases.
But let's not throw the handle after the cognac.
If the streaming information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear at us, the Czech mobile market may turn into a move.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the UOHS will only be difficult to remain intolerant to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And maybe we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech hymn has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national hymn.
On Sunday, on the occasion of the Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new records of the national hymn Kde domov moj (Where is my homeland?).
The hymn was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with choir and an instrumental version.
The song is assured by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the arrangements of the hymn.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek regards the Czech national song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhlas (the Czech public radio), he chose to interpret solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
“Since the beginning, I’ve tried to take care of both singers, as well as the choir, to have a good dictionary, so that we can understand the words they sing simultaneously,” he said.
The Czech national hymn will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde home moj retentit for the first time in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské theatre in Fidlovačka (Kermesse of the Councils), original Czech piece by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It became popular and people thought it was spontaneously appropriate.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couple became naturally an integral part of the national hymn.
He will remain one of the seven national symbols even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic.
