Southeasts demand a referendum in the United States
The Germans of the South demanded in 1945 that Šumava be integrated into the United States.
This comes from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of the South Bohemian).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to at least live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of the Southern Germans allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This comes from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is today deposited in the collections of Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
The Germans of Český Krumlov pray in the letter to the U.S. President not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemian) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
“We have understood the situation well and we want to be sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come to the German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,” the letter says, “People to whom the fate of the Šumava holds in heart.”
Given that the pledge with the Czechoslovakia is allegedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, unfair attitude, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the U.S. President to take in his hands the protectorate of the Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign state, which oppresses and destroys minorities and has in no way contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of a quarter of millions of people," the letter said.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire to vengeance of the Czech oppressors.
If the President of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether his residents wanted to be part of the United States, or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given the current knowledge of the postwar history, appear slightly naïve, according to some survivors, illustrate well the expectations of the Germans of the Southern of that time.
While the Czech Germans had to at least intervene that the issue of their expulsion from the Republic would be raised, very few of them would admit such a possibility.
Some were expecting that the United States and the UK would get some kind of autonomy for the Suezs.
Others believed they would just stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as German of České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
At the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the Holstein capture camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to learn the Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czechs would be profitable to them," Chalupa said.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war, according to him, would be expelled from the Republic, following the Beneš Decrees.
