Rats have feelings as well.
A rat or a cafard flees from danger, does that mean that he also feels scared?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced: many animals also have feelings.
But how can we verify that he experiences the same thing when he behaves in the same way as we?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles of answers to the question "What do you think to be true without having proof?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other state of consciousness without me or anyone else could prove it so far as we can’t prove that other human beings have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or generally consciousness, we will enter hardly practiced grounds because the Hardware does not correspond.
When a rat is in danger, he does the same as many other animals: he does death, escape or attack.
Human beings behave in the same way, so some scientists deduce a comparable subjective life.
However, I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the brain structure make the transposition of our subjective life to that of animals difficult.
One of the aspects is that the circuits associated almost always with human consciousness include the prefrontal side cortex (due to its participation in short-term memory and directional and executive functions).
This vast region is much more developed in human beings than in other primates and seems to be completely absent in other beings.
Therefore, at least for these aspects of our consciousness that depends on the prefrontal Cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that human being differs even from other primates.
Another significant particularity could reside in the linguistic nature of man: a large portion of his existence being connected to language, that often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we could exclude animals.
But even if consciousness should not depend on the language, it would certainly affect it, so that animal consciousness, regardless of how it is produced, would probably differ much from most of our consciousness states.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness can resemble in other animals.
If this, internally and subjectively, is neither allowed to measure nor, because of this particular Hardware, to analyze based on our own experience, then its observation poses major problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious life, but there is a further aspect of consciousness that should be more easily scientifically accessible.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined without taking into account their content, and that was exactly what happened in short-term studies on primates memory, especially with the example of visualisation.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on nervous correlations of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both can be identical or not.
Curiously, this approach also emphasizes the weight of the prefrontal Cortex in the realization of visualisation.
But what does it result from emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
