The Interview - The Blood Again
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of its foundation, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice because Hema-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained the public’s confidence that had been seriously embroidered by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by the Acquired Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and Hepatitis C Virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, the Government of Canada established a public investigation, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, in order to highlight the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such disaster from happening.
While Judge Krever was late to postpone his report, some provinces then set up a committee aiming to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gelineau Committee has fulfilled this mandate.
Following Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Québec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
“In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, only 38% of people still trusted the blood system in Quebec, the Dre Décary.
The situation was desperate.
With efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work on the ground for the following years, we have regained public confidence,” she said before proudly affirming that nearly 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in Hema-Québec at the beginning of 2008.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that “confidence is something extremely fragile.”
Since its creation, on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the principle of caution.
At that time, many cases of the human form of cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were attended in Europe since its founding in 1998.
“And we didn’t know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
It was then based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau reports, that when unknown and a serious disease can result from it, the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, which is characterized by a brain degeneration inevitablely leads to death, is to impose exceptional measures.
In April 1999, the blood of people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
But a few years ago, he was proved out of doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the principle of caution that was applied had meaning.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (TAN) that allow the presence of the virus itself to detect directly in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
TANs have been able to shorten the mute period, which extends between the time the person has been infected and the time the first virus can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
This has significantly reduced the risk of some donors being infected without knowing and unable to detect them.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people has the risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products every year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I think we can feel comfortable today to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health,” said the head of the Head of Headquarters of Hema-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogen is going to appear in the system.
Not later than last year on the island of the Reunion appeared the Chikungunya virus, which, like the Western Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect into the blood.
We need to be constantly vigilant,” Dr. Décary said before emphasising that in addition to a security supply, Héma-Québec should also provide adequate supply.
“Necessities increase because the population is ageing.
Since cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need recharge in red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the blood donors network, which is an average of only 3% of eligible Québecs for blood donation."
However, any healthy person aged 18 years and older who meets the eligibility criteria may give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is severe, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With these 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer give their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but especially to hold them up and encourage them to become a regular donor.
“Today’s life being so exhausted, we rarely find the time to spend an hour giving his blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone graffons, heart valves, eye globes and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only cord blood bank in Quebec.
The ombilical cordon that was once considered a biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood in stem cells that can be used to treat severe diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the banking of our millennium blood sample, and it is expected to take more than a thousand per year.
We should start offering it for greeps at the beginning of next year,” says Dre Décary, who describes this cordon blood sampling program as very popular.
"Several mothers are disappointed by not being able to access them," because Héma-Québec has no means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
