The psychology of the surencher: why is more money spent?
When selling at auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
Researchers in Neurology and Economy at the University of New York managed to update the neurological and economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behaviour.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings don’t want to be distant during this kind of competition, such as an eBay auction, and that’s why they even prefer to pay a too high price.
These researches have tried to set up a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" with the help of experimental auction sales.
One of the volunteer groups played the lotto, while the other group participated in a sales at the game auctions, while with the help of a functional magnetic resonance process (IRMf), the researchers analyzed the active brain areas of experimental subjects.
In both games, the participants could earn money, but during the sale of auctions whose essential element is the surrender of a third, the whole set being under the brain trunk, called striatum, was moving intensely during the loss of the game.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the "self-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
That is why, according to the researchers, the rise of prices is explained by the escape in front of the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, economics members of this research group continued financial monitoring analysis.
During these three groups, three groups faced a partner in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product concerned, and thus they carried out their introduction.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they were going out of the game, then they would receive additional $15 in reward.
While the third group received him these 15 dollars before the auctions, the members of the group also lost that money in case they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was placed at one on victory, while at the other on failure.
By so proving the hypothesis of neurologs, players' team members were willing to "confront failure" bets higher than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
“These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
In fact, each of them explained the phenomena found in auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade at risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to eliminate the contradiction between the two theories by creating, now, a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
About half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
It is estimated that the patients carrying the hepatitis virus in Hungary are a hundred miles away, but only seven miles follow treatment. This is due to the fact that often the patients do not know they are carrying the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to liver infections and caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Liver and yellow inflammation are characteristic, but pathogenic agents and diseases generated differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g. food or contaminated water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic liquids (sperm, vaginal secretion, salt).
For travellers, it is highly recommended to vaccinate against A and B viruses. There is no C vaccine.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming contaminated foods, generally accompanied by a poor general state, weakness, stomach pain and nausea.
Then it develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible yellowness, the seeds become brighter and the urine takes a darker color. Cure may take two to three weeks.
Every year around the world, one million people die from the most severe form of this pathology, such as liver cancer or cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know about the virus, because the pathogenic gene destroys the liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms only appear after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular testing tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people with blood transfusion before 1991, drug consumers and tattoos.
Currently, 200 million patients with chronic type C hepatitis are counted worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is recommended to consult your doctor treating as soon as observation of unknown origin symptoms.
The disease can be healed if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
The 30th of September is the World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by the organizations representing the sick in the four corners of the world.
Its goal is to draw attention to the chronic liver cirrhosis caused by viruses, to the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
