The smart car imitates the burdon
What method would be better to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if it is not the imitation of an obstacle detector already exists in nature?
Like, for example, the bees.
In the incredible project presented at CEATEC, which took place in Japan, bore bees gave Nissan’s engineers the strategic start idea to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini-robot car, a bio-inspired BR23C self-robot control system, which has equipped the quality of bees, the ultimate goal is to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
When flying, each bees forms its own, oval-shaped space, which in fact looks much like our secure protective cock, Kazuhhiro Doi, director of the Department of Research and Development and Public Relations of the brand, explained at the exhibition.
The bees' face eye plays a major role, as it is able to see in all directions, in a angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the face eye, engineers approached the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the board microprocessor, which transforms it into avoidance manoeuvre immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second, then the mini auto robot, imitating the bees movements, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from a sufficient angle to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance maneuver takes place entirely instinctively.
“If it wasn’t so, the mini-robot couldn’t react fast enough to avoid the obstacle,” Toshiyuki Andoh, director of Mobility Laboratory and Robotic Car Project said.
It must react instinctively and instantly, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and inner layer of the protective cover, a layer where the collision is currently considered inevitable.
All this process must reflect what the bees do to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in an eyeliner.
In contrast to the bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonal, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that the bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use rotating movement, acceleration as well as slowing as manoeuvres available to the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and the energy concentration is larger, making their life longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is essential, not data processing, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should only process a few signals incoming per second, and respond to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with the intuitive logic based on the data of previous manoeuvres, so it only uses dozens of kilo-octets of memory continuously.
We don't need memory of a giga-octet capacity, or even mega-octet.
This is the first step towards the design of an instant avoidance technology. According to Nissan’s estimates, this system will enter the series cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles on its path.
