In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and 12.9 per cent compared to the August 2007 - the Hungarian Central Bureau of Statistics reported.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1% compared to those of July 2008, while compared to those of one year earlier, they declined by 3.9%.
As a result of domestic and export price fluctuations, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 percent compared to those of the previous month, and by 3.2 percent compared to those of the previous year.
The domestic industrial sales prices have only increased to a lesser extent: by 0.1 percent, compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry have only suffered a significant increase of 0.1 percent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price rise was observed in the leather and shoe manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first production of bags and belts with a monthly rise of 4.6 per cent, then the production of shoes with 2.5 per cent monthly rise.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials has resulted in a significant monthly increase in prices in the manufacturing sector of chemicals and products (1.6%).
A deflation resulted in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of machines and electrical apparatus (0,9 per cent), as well as a minimum increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
Prices of paper production, editing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry saw a rise between 0.2 percent and 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which represent a significant weight in national industrial operations, prices have risen by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the effect of the rising gas prices established by the authorities since July 1st.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account domestic sales of processing sectors, these are oil processing prices that have experienced the most significant increase (32.4%).
In the metallurgy industry, prices were increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the important field of food, beverage and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price declines have occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of machines and electrical appliances (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the processing industry, the price rise has evolved from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
In the whole processing industry, prices rose by 10.2% over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors have exceeded 18.7 per cent that of the previous year.
Among the domestic commerce groups and according to the sectoral assignment, in August, these are the investment profit-initiator sectors that showed the most significant increase in monthly prices (0.7 percent).
In the production sectors of consumer goods, prices increased by 0.3 percent, while those in the sectors of energy producers and materials for subsequent processing did not have any changes compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the most significant increase in the energy and material production sectors for subsequent transformation was observed (16.8 per cent).
In the production sectors of consumer goods, an inflation of 6.8 per cent was measured, while in the profit-initiating sectors, a decrease of 1.4 per cent.
The export prices of the industry in HUF increased by 1.1% in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9% in 12 months.
